Part B. Simulate a Network of LIF Neurons

Q5. Extended code to n excitatory Neuron.

Two neurons are modelled such that none of them are connected, M defines the connectivity matrix. Since the input current is only supplied to the first neuron, upon crossing the threshold it has the potential to fire. but for the second one the potential should decrease to it's defined resting potential.
number_of_neurons=2;
M=zeros(number_of_neurons); % connectivity matrix
T=1000; % total time in ms (Simulating 1s or 1000ms)
i=5; %1.355;%0.76;
v_init=-60;
sigma=28.05; %28.05;
inhibitory_neuron_flag=0;
visible=T; %(visible range in raster plot) (in ms)
[V,CV]=get_membraneV_n(v_init,i,T,'on',M,sigma,visible); %LIF simulation
figure,
plot(0:0.1:T,V(:,1),'LineWidth',0.1);set(gca,'LineWidth',1.5);hold on;
plot(0:0.1:T,V(:,2),'LineWidth',1.5);set(gca,'LineWidth',1.5)
xlabel('Time (ms)','FontName','Times New Roman',"FontSize",16);
ylabel('membrane potential (mV)','FontName','Times New Roman',"FontSize",16);
xlim([0 1000])
hold off

Description:

The raster plot and the corresponds to their respective outcome. get_membraneV_n function accomodateds for n neurons.

Q6. Connect the neurons.

The neurons are now connected and accounted for by means of a connectivity matrix M, the neurons connected to the first neuron now given enough current should be able to fire.
T=1000; % total time in ms (Simulating 1s or 1000ms)
i=5; %1.355;%0.76;
v_init=-60;
sigma=28.05; %28.05;
number_of_neurons=20;
inhibitory_neuron_flag=0;
visible=500; %(visible range in raster plot) (in ms)
M=connect_neurons(number_of_neurons,inhibitory_neuron_flag,'on');
[V,CV]=get_membraneV_n(v_init,i,T,'on',M,sigma,visible); %LIF simulation

Description:

The diagonal matrices were set to 0 to ensure there were no self connecting neurons. The self-connection could mean the there would always be the possibility for the neurons to be fired after every 1.5ms. Accounting for the 1.5ms delay time, the membrane potentials are now updated for every neuron over time.

Q9 and Q10. Introducing Inhibitory neurons and plotting distribution.

Here, 20% inhibitory neurons are added in the function connect_neurons by keeping the number of total neurons fixed to 50.
The inhibitory neurons have the following properties as given in the assignment-
(a) Inhibitory neurons do not connect to other inhibitory neurons.
(b) Inhibitory neurons decrease the membrane potential of post-synaptic excitatory neurons.
(c) Excitatory neurons increase the membrane potential of both excitatory and inhibitory neurons.
We expect to observe the firings to be more discrete compared to the earlier excitatory case.
T=1000; % total time in ms (Simulating 1s or 1000ms)
i=5; %1.355;%0.76;
v_init=-60;
sigma=28.05; %28.05;
inhibitory_neuron_flag=1;
visible=500; %(visible range in raster plot) (in ms)
number_of_neurons=50;
M=connect_neurons(number_of_neurons,inhibitory_neuron_flag,'on');
[V,CV]=get_membraneV_n(v_init,i,T,'on',M,sigma,visible); %LIF simulation

Description:

The firing patterns for each neurons becomes discrete upon the introduction of the inhibitory neurons as the inhibitory neurons are expected to reduce the membrane potentials for the excitatory neurons at the same time less number of connections as the inhibitatory neurons don't connect to other inhibitory neurons. The distribution mean is close to 0.9 to 1 indicating the inter spike interval for the neurons are grossly different although following a regular pattern over time for each neuron.

Conclusion:

The overall assignment was really interesting and challenging as it enabled to undertand me the following points-
  1. How neural firings could be modelled using differential equations. I have solved it using Julia differential equations package as well, adding this for note to myself (/Users/afaiyaz/Documents/2021/Spring/BCS547/Assignment_1/Julia).
  2. LIF model follows the exact charging rule (except for the spike) of the RC circuits.
  3. Spike rates increase with the increase of charge through input I. The overall dynamics of an LIF is very simple without the variability of the input with a gaussian. The standard deviation of the input can simulate dynamic behavior of real neuron.
  4. The behavior of the neurons in a network is more insightful. It highlights the connectivity dynamics and types of neural behavior in possible for a real neuron.

Local Functions (Part B)

function M=connect_neurons(n,inh_flag,figon)
% get M : introducing inhibitory neuron if inh_flag is 1 (9)
M=1.5* rand(n) .* ~eye(n); % connection matrix
if inh_flag==1
n_inh=int16(0.20 * n);
if n_inh ~=0
M(n-n_inh+1:end,n-n_inh+1:end)=0;
M(n-n_inh+1:end,1:end)=M(n-n_inh+1:end,1:end)*-1;
end
end
if strcmp(figon,'on')
figure,imagesc(M); colorbar
if inh_flag~=1
title('No inhibitory neurons added.')
end
end
end
function [V,CV] = get_membraneV_n(v_init,i,T,figon,M,sigma,visible)
% get_membraneV - Implements a function that returns the membrane potential
% for arbitrary input currents i(t)
% Syntax: [output1,output2] = get_membraneV (input1,input2,input3)
%
% Inputs:
% v_init - initial V
% i - Input Current (mean)
% T - The total simulation time
% figon - Determines the plot
% M - Matrix of connected neurons
% sigma - Standard deviation of input current (Optional)
% visible - visible range in the raster plot (ms)
%
% Outputs:
% V - Membrane_potential response to the input i % Note i is not
% exactly the current; there's simplification of constants there.
% ISI - Interspike Interval
% CV - Coeffiecient of Variation
% Example:
% Line 1 of example
% Line 2 of example
%
% Other m-files required: none
% Subfunctions: none
% MAT-files required: none
%
% See also: OTHER_FUNCTION_NAME1, OTHER_FUNCTION_NAME2
% Author : Abrar Faiyaz (ORCID iD: https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0666-3051 )
% email : abrarfaiyaz.iutcse@gmail.com
% Created on : 14-Feb-2021
% Last revision : NONE
% ------------- BEGIN CODE --------------
% T=1000; % total time in ms (Simulating 1s or 1000ms)
% i=0.9;
% v_init=-65;
dt=0.1; %step size is 0.1ms
v_reset=-70; %mV %70
v_rest=-65; %mV %65
v_thresh=-50; %mV
EPSP_delay=1.5; %ms
n=size(M,1);
% M=2* rand(n) .* ~eye(n); % connection matrix
spiking_voltage=40; %mv
tau=50; %ms
time=0:dt:T;
if isempty(sigma)
I=ones(size(time)).*i;
else
I=normrnd(i,sigma,size(time));
% hist(I)
end
V=NaN(length(time),n);
tol=0.001;
spike_timestamp={[]}; %=zeros(length(time),n);
for j=1:n
spike_timestamp{j}=[];
end
for t=1:length(time)
for j=1:n
if time(t)==0
V(t,j)=v_init;
elseif time(t)>0 && time(t)<=T
% if the membrane potential is around the spiking voltage, then reset
if abs(V(t-1,j) - spiking_voltage) < tol
V(t,j) = v_reset;
else
if j==1
V(t,j) = V(t-1,j) + dt* ((-1/tau) * (V(t-1,j)-v_rest) + I(t-1));
else
V(t,j) = V(t-1,j) + dt* ((-1/tau) * (V(t-1,j)-v_rest));
end
end
% Make sure the connection matrix gets addressed at this point
if time(t)>EPSP_delay
for k=1:n
if abs(V(t-int32(EPSP_delay/dt),k) - spiking_voltage) < tol
% if there was a spike before 1.5ms from somewhere k
V(t,j) = V(t,j)+ M(k,j); % M(k,j) spike from k, ...
% resulting voltage increment in j
end
end
end
% if voltage is greater than threshold but did not reach the
% spiking potential then spike will occur
if (V(t,j) >= v_thresh) && abs(V(t,j) - spiking_voltage) > tol
V(t,j) = spiking_voltage;
spike_timestamp{j}=[spike_timestamp{j},time(t)]; %(t,j)=time(t);
elseif V(t,j) <= v_reset % if below reset potential, then stays at
% reset potential
V(t,j)=v_reset;
end
end
end
end
ISI={};
CV=zeros(1,n);
for j=1:n
ISI{j}=diff(spike_timestamp{j});
CV(j)=std(ISI{j})/mean(ISI{j});
end
% CV=mean(ISI)/std(ISI); %Coefficient of Variation
% calculate mean ISI (Inter Spike Interval)
% => mean(diff(spike_timestamp))
% to find the distribution of the ISI => diff(spike_timestamp)
if strcmp(figon,'on')
% figure,
% Raster plot
K=V;
K(V<0)=0;
K(V>30)=1;
figure('Position',[0 0 1000 500])
subplot(1,2,1);
for p=1:size(V,2)
l=plot(0:0.1:T,K(:,p)'.*p,'s');
l.MarkerFaceColor = l.Color;
hold on
end
xlim([0 visible]);
hold off
% figure,
% h=subplot(1,2,1);
% sampling_rate=10000;
% rasterplot(find(K'),n,visible./dt,h,sampling_rate);
xlabel('Time')
ytickformat('%d')
yticks(1:n);
ylim([0.5,n+0.5])
xlabel('Time (ms)','FontName','Times New Roman','FontSize',...
16,'FontWeight','normal');
ylabel('Neuron #','FontName','Times New Roman','FontSize',16,...
'FontWeight','normal')
title('Raster Plot','FontName','Times New Roman','FontSize',16,...
'FontWeight','bold');
set(gca,'LineWidth',1.5)
set(gca,'TickLength',[0 0])
hold off
subplot(1,2,2)
histogram(CV,'Normalization','pdf');hold on;
[f1,xi1]=ksdensity(CV);
plot(xi1,f1,'r','LineWidth',1.5,'DisplayName','ksdensity');
xlabel('Time Bin (ms)','FontName','Times New Roman','FontSize',16,...
'FontWeight','normal');
ylabel('Histogram','FontName','Times New Roman','FontSize',16,...
'FontWeight','normal')
title('{\it C_{v}} Distribution','FontName','Times New Roman','FontSize',16,...
'FontWeight','bold');
legend;
set(gca,'LineWidth',1.5)
end
% ------------- END OF CODE -------------
end
